But you realize that there's a way to explain why the Higgs boson would be light, and that's

22:10.260 --> 22:16.860
to invoke some deep, elegant mathematical principle that would explain why the theory is actually

22:16.860 --> 22:20.620
more constrained.

22:20.620 --> 22:27.180
Here is one such deep, elegant mathematical principle, it's called supersymmetry.

22:27.180 --> 22:32.940
Symmetry is some deep, elegant mathematical relation between force particles and matter

22:32.940 --> 22:33.940
particles.

22:33.940 --> 22:34.940
And they all have silly names.

22:34.940 --> 22:40.740
If an electron is a matter particle, there's a silly force particle, they say electron.

22:40.740 --> 22:43.220
You have to get your kick somewhere.

22:43.220 --> 22:44.620
So what?

22:44.620 --> 22:53.260
So this ends up solving this puzzle that we had found.

22:53.260 --> 22:57.060
Symmetry, because every particle has a copy, gives you new particles.

22:57.060 --> 23:00.220
This theory predicts new particles.

23:00.220 --> 23:05.660
So lesson number one, moe particles, moe problems.

23:05.660 --> 23:08.460
I want this all to be on board with that.

23:08.460 --> 23:09.460
So what happened?

23:09.460 --> 23:12.820
Oh, this theory has more particles.

23:12.820 --> 23:14.140
So what?

23:14.140 --> 23:18.100
It turns out, the moment you put these new particles in, and you knew exactly what they

23:18.100 --> 23:26.660
were, because for every proton, there's a super proton, all this stuff, protons suddenly

23:26.660 --> 23:30.300
