23:47.180 --> 23:50.860
So you should think about, how do we have a bound that is longer than the age of space

23:50.860 --> 23:53.100
time itself?

23:53.100 --> 23:58.940
But protons are pretty darn stable, so that's not a good feature.

23:58.940 --> 24:04.540
But we're thinking, you know, this is some weird practical problem, and this is this elegant,

24:04.540 --> 24:09.900
deep mathematical thing was so beautiful, let's try to save it.

24:09.900 --> 24:16.940
And what we do is we put a bandaid, a mathematical bandaid, and we invent some additional symmetry.

24:17.060 --> 24:23.060
It's not deep, not elegant, but we just say, maybe there's some rule that prohibits these

24:23.060 --> 24:26.700
interactions, and it has this silly name, r-parity.

24:26.700 --> 24:31.460
And I will bet you nobody in this entire institute knows what the r means in r-parity.

24:31.460 --> 24:34.700
I don't know.

24:34.700 --> 24:40.180
But what this r-parity does, mathematically, you apply r-parity, and that means that the

24:40.180 --> 24:46.420
interactions that would have caused the protons to decay are no longer allowed.

24:46.420 --> 24:49.180
And it looks like everything starts to work again.

24:49.180 --> 24:54.220
You solve your deep elegant problem, and the immediate other problem that comes up seems

24:54.220 --> 24:57.780
to be okay, and you start feeling pretty good.

24:57.780 --> 25:01.220
You bring your team of graduate students, and you look at this, and you say, hey, what

25:01.220 --> 25:03.420
else does this theory do for us?

25:03.420 --> 25:12.460
Well, with all of these new particles, and some reason, some parity, it turns out the

25:12.460 --> 25:16.620
lightest new particle is stable.

25:16.620 --> 25:22.540
So the reason why electrons don't decay into neutrinos, which are these other funny particles,

25:22.540 --> 25:25.980
is because electrons are the lightest particle that carry electric charge.

25:25.980 --> 25:30.540
There's no way to conserve charge if that electron decayed.

25:30.540 --> 25:39.140
So the lightest new particle which carries r-charge is stable, cosmologically stable.

25:39.140 --> 25:44.380
And it is at this point that we think, hey, you know, I heard something about cosmologically

25:44.380 --> 25:45.700
stable new particles.

25:45.700 --> 25:50.260
Oh, it was our friends downstairs, as we go down the stairs, and they say, what do you

25:50.260 --> 25:52.220
know about dark matter?

