40:36.140 --> 40:39.020
But when we do theoretical physics,

40:39.020 --> 40:41.420
we are exploring what types of models

40:41.420 --> 40:43.460
can explain the dark matter puzzle

40:43.460 --> 40:46.940
and what can we learn from those mathematical models.

40:46.940 --> 40:50.380
And like any good crime procedural,

40:50.380 --> 40:52.980
there is a motive, means, and opportunity.

40:52.980 --> 40:56.260
A mathematical model for dark matter

40:56.260 --> 40:58.340
answers these questions.

40:58.340 --> 41:00.860
First one is, what is it?

41:00.860 --> 41:04.460
Some super symmetric partner, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

41:04.460 --> 41:06.820
The next thing is, how did it get here?

41:06.820 --> 41:11.340
You have to explain what mechanism created this particle.

41:11.340 --> 41:13.860
Then most of the particles that we know of

41:13.860 --> 41:15.540
are actually unstable.

41:15.540 --> 41:19.620
You have to explain, why is that particle still around?

41:19.620 --> 41:21.580
And given that we've been searching for dark matter

41:21.580 --> 41:23.780
for 30 years, then your theory has

41:23.780 --> 41:27.020
to say why we haven't found it yet.

41:27.020 --> 41:31.820
And any theory worth its weight will tell you,

41:31.820 --> 41:35.300
and this is how you will discover this type of particle.

41:35.300 --> 41:37.940
It'll give you something falsifiable.

41:37.940 --> 41:40.780
And so for the weekly interacting massive particle,

41:40.780 --> 41:43.100
there is some deep, elegant mathematical symmetry

41:43.100 --> 41:45.460
that explains to you what this new particle is.

41:45.460 --> 41:48.900
And that was very deep, and exciting, and meaningful.

41:48.900 --> 41:51.060
Then there's a series of answers.

41:51.060 --> 41:52.140
How did it get here?

41:52.140 --> 41:54.140
